As stated in comments, your code doesn&#39;t even compile properly.  So you need to fix that first.  Your second use of `?:` is malformed.

`val1 &gt; val2 &gt; val3` evaluates to a `bool`, which when converted to an integer will be either 1 (`true`) or 0 (`false`).  And any integer evaluated as a boolean will be either `true` (non-zero) or `false` (zero).  So that is why your code ends up outputting 0 (if it compiles at all), because you end up with a `false` result value being converted to an integer.

You would need to use something more like this instead:

```
cout &lt;&lt; &quot;the greatest between &quot; &lt;&lt; val1 &lt;&lt; &quot;, &quot; &lt;&lt; val2 &lt;&lt; &quot; and &quot; &lt;&lt; val3 &lt;&lt; &quot; is &quot; &lt;&lt; ((val1 &gt; val2) ? ((val1 &gt; val3) ? val1 : val3) : ((val2 &gt; val3) ? val2 : val3)) &lt;&lt; endl;
```

But, doing all those comparisons in one statement is not very readable.  You should use a local variable to hold the result of the comparison, then print out the variable, eg:

```
greatest = (val1 &gt; val2)
            ? ((val1 &gt; val3) ? val1 : val3)
            : ((val2 &gt; val3) ? val2 : val3);
cout &lt;&lt; &quot;the greatest between &quot; &lt;&lt; val1 &lt;&lt; &quot;, &quot; &lt;&lt; val2 &lt;&lt; &quot; and &quot; &lt;&lt; val3 &lt;&lt; &quot; is &quot; &lt;&lt; greatest &lt;&lt; endl;
```

Or:

```
greatest = (val1 &gt; val2) ? val1 : val2;
greatest = (greatest &gt; val3) ? greatest : val3;
cout &lt;&lt; &quot;the greatest between &quot; &lt;&lt; val1 &lt;&lt; &quot;, &quot; &lt;&lt; val2 &lt;&lt; &quot; and &quot; &lt;&lt; val3 &lt;&lt; &quot; is &quot; &lt;&lt; greatest &lt;&lt; endl;
```

Now, that being said, using `switch` in this situation does not make sense, and won&#39;t really help you.  It would end up looking something like this:

```
switch (val1 &gt; val2)
{
    case true:
        switch (val1 &gt; val3)
        {
            case true:
                greatest = val1;
                break;
           case false:
               greatest = val3;
               break;
        }
        break;
    case false:
        switch (val2 &gt; val3)
        {
            case true:
                greatest = val2;
                break;
           case false:
               greatest = val3;
               break;
        }
        break;
};

cout &lt;&lt; &quot;the greatest between &quot; &lt;&lt; val1 &lt;&lt; &quot;, &quot; &lt;&lt; val2 &lt;&lt; &quot; and &quot; &lt;&lt; val3 &lt;&lt; &quot; is &quot; &lt;&lt; greatest &lt;&lt; endl
```

Or:

```
switch (val1 &gt; val2)
{
    case true:
        greatest = val1;
        break;
    case false:
        greatest = val2;
        break;
}

switch (greatest &gt; val3)
{
    case false:
        greatest = val3;
        break;
}

cout &lt;&lt; &quot;the greatest between &quot; &lt;&lt; val1 &lt;&lt; &quot;, &quot; &lt;&lt; val2 &lt;&lt; &quot; and &quot; &lt;&lt; val3 &lt;&lt; &quot; is &quot; &lt;&lt; greatest &lt;&lt; endl;
```

Which is really no better than using `if`/`else` blocks:

```
if (val1 &gt; val2)
{
    if (val1 &gt; val3)
        greatest = val1;
    else
        greatest = val3;
}
else
{
    if (val2 &gt; val3)
        greatest = val2;
    else
        greatest = val3;
}

cout &lt;&lt; &quot;the greatest between &quot; &lt;&lt; val1 &lt;&lt; &quot;, &quot; &lt;&lt; val2 &lt;&lt; &quot; and &quot; &lt;&lt; val3 &lt;&lt; &quot; is &quot; &lt;&lt; greatest &lt;&lt; endl
```

Or:

```
if (val1 &gt; val2)
    greatest = val1;
else
    greatest = val2;

if (val3 &gt; greatest)
    greatest = val3;

cout &lt;&lt; &quot;the greatest between &quot; &lt;&lt; val1 &lt;&lt; &quot;, &quot; &lt;&lt; val2 &lt;&lt; &quot; and &quot; &lt;&lt; val3 &lt;&lt; &quot; is &quot; &lt;&lt; greatest &lt;&lt; endl;
```

